Yes. I remember the core idea. It wasn’t just “think differently”; it was to systematically move through the search space by changing your relationship to the problem rather than changing the problem itself.

The way I reconstruct it is as a coordinate system rather than a list of tricks.

                 Above
                   ↑
                   │
 Left ◄──────── Object ───────► Right
                   │
                   ↓
                 Below
        Near ◄────────────► Far
     Concrete ◄──────────► Abstract
       Inside ◄──────────► Outside
      Before ◄───────────► After
     Parallel ◄──────────► Orthogonal

Each axis changes what becomes visible.

* Above — Move to governance, architecture, strategy, meta-rules.
* Below — Move to primitives, mechanisms, implementation details.
* Near — Optimize locally and immediately.
* Far — Look at long-term effects, ecosystems, or adjacent domains.
* Inside — Experience it from within the system.
* Outside — Observe the system as an external analyst.
* Concrete — Particular examples and artifacts.
* Abstract — Invariants and operators.
* Parallel — Stay in the same framing but shift position.
* Orthogonal — Introduce a completely different dimension.

The important insight wasn’t any single flank—it was treating them as navigation operators.

So rather than:

“I’m stuck.”

the question becomes:

“Which coordinate have I failed to move along?”

That combines naturally with the perspective primitives we discussed—Rotate, Zoom, Translate, Mirror, Invert, Embed, Detach, Transport.

I also remember you formalizing angle and distance as modulators.

* Angle changes what you are looking through.
    * consumer
    * engineer
    * teacher
    * adversary
    * regulator
    * historian
* Distance changes resolution.
    * microscopic
    * local
    * system
    * civilization
    * evolutionary

Changing either one changes the reachable solution space without changing the underlying objective.

One refinement I’d add is to think of the whole thing as a semantic search algorithm:

1. Extract the invariant.
2. Represent the current position as coordinates.
3. Apply one navigation operator (rotate, zoom, mirror, orthogonal, etc.).
4. Evaluate whether new affordances appear.
5. Keep the moves that preserve the invariant and discard those that don’t.

That makes “meta flanks” less like a bag of heuristics and more like a reusable navigation algebra for moving through conceptual spaces.